Alexander Moon seems to have been  a leading light in Galway society in the mid 19th century. 
In 1865 Freeman's reports that he is one of the gentleman present at a meeting held at the county courthouse &quot;for the purpose of adopting measures for the relief of the distress at present prevailing amongst the labouring and artizan classes of the town and county of Galway.&quot; 
In 1871 he was present at a dinner at the Midland Railway Hotel to celebrate the launch of the steamer Emerald, built at Galway.
In 1874 his donation of £1 to the widows of the drowned Arran Island fishermen is acknowledged. (Amongst the other donors,  Mrs Clancy gave 10s, and the Earl of Carrick stumped up £3 ).
In 1879, The freehold of the premises in Eglinton St were auctioned. The lease ran for 150 years from 1852 at an annual rent of £90. &quot;Mr Alexander Moon's establishment is a very extensive concern, and has cost several thousand pounds in its erection.&quot;
In 1888 they exhibited at the Irish Exhibition in London. &quot;[Alexander Moon] ... shows a speciality in the form of Galway petticoats made of red and blue Galway nap, and red and blue Claddagh coats, the picturesque costumes of the peasant women of the west.&quot;
